White Wine Quality Analysis by Vijayasarathi

The data set we have is about the whitewine which is rated by atleast 3 wine experts. This tidy data set contains 4,898 white wines with 11 variables on quantifying the chemical properties of each wine. rating values ranges from 0 (very bad) to 10 (very excellent). As part of this analysis we will create different graph and calculate statistical parameters and values which will help us to conclude the chemical properties influence on the quality of white wines.

Observations :

Mean residual sugar level is 6.391 g/l, but there is a sample of very sweet wine with 65.8 g/l (an outlier). Mean free sulfur dioxide is 35.31 ppm. Max value is 289 which is quite high as 75% is 46 ppm. PH of wine is within range from 2.72 till 3.82, mean 3.2. There is no basic wines in this dataset (no high pH levels). Alcohol: lightest wine is 8%, strongest is 14.2. Minimum quality mark is 3, mean 5.878, highest is 9.

Reflection

i took white wine data from the suggested data with multiple reasons in mind to choose this data set. i never had a alcohol, never tested as well but through this exercise i want to challenge my self if i can work on something where i have no experience. Struggle : though looking at each parameter and observing its impact was interesting, but didnt give bigger picture or didnt help me to understand the parameters for famous wine. multi variate analysis and correlation across all other parameters gave me a better direction. i decided the parameters and variables once i got the correlation across the parameters and impact ful parameters.

i was trying to create the correlation map for different parameters using the ggpair but the picture didn’t come well though i used the small alpha value, then i switched it to ggcorr and picture looked better.

Success: After analyzing the data i concluded the below items :

When alcohol percentage decreases, density grows. No correlation between acidity and density. Total sulfur dioxide and level of residual sugar are positively correlated. Correlation shows higher value. White wine density and residual sugar level have positive correlation. Alcohol level of white wine decreases with the growth of residual sugar level. Wine with high alcohol percentage has quality level 7, wine with less alcohol percentage is quality level 5. Mostly frequent quality levels are 5 and 6. Per analysis we can conclude that experts’ decisions on wine quality levels are based on their personal testes or could depend on other variables like year of production, ingredients used (ex : grape types), wine brand etc. as only one variable (alcohol level) has correlation with quality of wine.

Ideas for improvement : For future exploration of this data I would pick one category of wine (for example, quality level 3-4, 5-7, 8-9) to look at the patterns which can appear in each of these three buckets. For advance analytics we can include how the other cold beverages performing compare to wine. Also, we can compare the color, what if we introduce a blue wine how the trend will be all that predictive analytics. may be we can add more parameter into consideration and bigger parameters will help us to narrow down the results.
